PK Analysis Sample for Single Ascending Dose Data

## Load needed libraries
libraries <- c("tidyverse","ggplot2","shiny","shinydashboard","xgxr","dplyr","DBI","tidyr","stringr","ggpubr","gridExtra","xgxr")

Introduction

Analysis of biometric data from pharmacokinetics experiment of the anti-asthmatic drug theophylline.

data(Theoph)

Additional datasets:

  • demog.csv: demographics dataset characterizing the subjects
  • il5.csv: This dataset contains % inhibition of stimulated IL-5 release by PBMC at hour 0 and hour 24.

Data join on theophylline data.

  • a_Theoph includes all subjects’ data in Theoph joined with demographic data (using the correct dplyr join function) from dm.csv and il5 inhibition data from il5.csv.
  • Included only the subjects from Theoph in the resulting joined dataset. Subjects in Theoph will be included in the analysis population.
  • Created data frame a_Theoph with the following columns:
    • Subject: Subject ID from Theoph
    • SEX: Sex from dm.csv
    • Age: Age from dm.csv
    • Dose: Dose from Theoph
    • Time: Time from Theoph
    • Conc: conc from Theop
    • il5PCTI: % IL-5 inhibition from il5.csv

Summary of Theophylline concentrations by gender

Each subject colored by gender shown in above graph and table to illustrate particular trends over time by group. Concentrations tend to peak for all subjects by 5 hours with peak concentrations largely being higher in male subjects as indicated by maximal peak concentration in males compared to females of 11.4 mg/ml versus 9.03 mg/ml in females. Similarly, mean (SD) of concentrations of Theophylline over 24 hr are reach higher levels in males than females, 5.6 (3.1) and 4.4 (2.5), respectively.

Calculate AUC

AUC (based on the linear trapezoidal rule) applied to a_Theoph.

trapezoid <- function(indf) {

  outdf <- indf %>%
    group_by(Subject) %>%
    mutate(conc2 = ifelse(Time>0,lag(Conc),0),time2=ifelse(Time>0,lag(Time),0))%>%mutate(Trap=((Time-time2)*(Conc+conc2))/2)%>%mutate(AUC=cumsum(Trap))
##

  return(outdf %>% as.data.frame())
}

trapezoid(a_Theoph)->AUC_calc_ref
trapezoid(a_Theoph)->a_Theoph

Analysis: AUC

Estimates of the pharmacokinetic (PK) property, area under the curve (AUC), for the drug Theophylline based on the available data.

PK Analysis assumptions

1.) Trends examined from dose-dependent pharmacokinetic data assumes subjects respond similarly to drug irrespective of age, gender and other potentially confounding covariates. Also interpretation is limited by low N in each group. 2.) Numeric dose was broken into tertiles and tertiles were assumed to correspond to categorical designation of incremental dose increase of low, middle and high dose. 3.) Time values converted to categorical values (binned) with solution provided in above code.

Interpretation of PK and AUC data

Concentration of Theophylline by dose category shows those in the high dose group achieve higher concentrations over 24 hr than the other two lower dose groups, but this is slightly lagged in comparison to lower dose groups which suggests slower absorption. This is further reinforced by the normalized concentration of Theophylline by dose category plot,which shows better absorption of the low dose groups. Overall AUC also shows an gender effect with median (IQR) values lower for females than for males,87.4 (8.5) and 121 (24), respectively.The same was trend was observed for Cmax. Due to low N and lack of robust trend, a weak non-significant linear relationship with both AUC and Cmax were observed with numeric dose values.

Interpretation of IL-5 inhibition and correlations

Overall no significant relationships were observed between percent change of IL-5 inhibition from baseline with numeric dose, AUC, and Cmax. With dose and AUC, an inverse non-significant linear relationship was observed between percent change of IL-5 inhibition from baseline.
